Pre-heat your #oven{} to 220 degrees. Peel and finely dice the @red onion{1}(peeled and finely diced) and the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and finely diced). Slice the @courgette{3} lengthways into ½ centimetre strips. Chop the @cherry tomatoes{⅔} in half.

Next slice ¾ of your @mozzarella{1} into slices, as thin as you can (keep ¼ for your salad). Press #kitchen towel{} or a clean #tea towel{} onto each slice to soak up as much excess moisture as possible.

Fry 1/2 cup of the diced red onion and the garlic in @olive oil{1%tbsp} on med/low heat for around ~{5%minutes}, or until soft. You can start step 5 at the same time to save some time.

Add in the @tomato passata{1} with @salt{1/4%tsp}, the @dried oregano{1%tsp} and a few grinds of @black pepper{}. Bubble the mixture away for ~{5%minutes}, then remove from the heat to cool down a little.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Once hot fry off the courgette strips in batches. Cook them for ~{1%minute} on each side and then keep to the side. Do not overcrowd the pan as this will stew the courgette rather than brown it off.

Put enough of your passata in an ovenproof #dish{} to thinly cover the bottom. Cover this with a layer of your courgettes. Next layer on ½ the mozzarella, some @basil{}(torn), ½ the @pine nuts{2} and ½ the @grated hard Italian style cheese{2%tbsp}.

Spread on another layer of passata, followed by courgettes, mozzarella, basil and pine nuts. Finally add one more layer of passata and top your parmigiana with the remaining hard cheese and the @panko breadcrumbs{1%cup}. Bake in the oven for ~{15%minutes}.

Tear up a small handful of basil leaves and the remaining mozzarella. Toss these into the cherry tomatoes with @olive oil{1%tsp} and a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Serve the parmigiana with your salad and @foccacia{1} on the side.

> When we started Hello Fresh from Patrick's living room a few short years ago we wanted to make dinner time easy. Whilst the emphasis has always been on quick and tasty, there are certain recipes that deserve a bit more time and this parmigiana is one of those. We recommend enlisting a sous chef to help you with the prep. They'll be more than happy to help once they smell what's on the menu!